   National Health Service Corps SEARCH: Alaskan Exposure Program

   Experience the challenges, rewards and cultural diversity that health
   care practice in underserved communities can offer by becoming a member
   of Alaskaâ€™s health care delivery team!

   What is Alaskan Exposure?

   The Alaskan Exposure program seeks to provide students in primary care
   health professions with unique and rewarding rotations in underserved
   communities. Teaming up with primary care providers, students have the
   opportunity to experience primary care first-hand. The program is a
   collaboration of communities, health care facilities, health
   practitioners, students and academic institutions.

   Funding is provided through the
   National Health Service Corps
   Students/Residents Experiences
   And Rotations in Community Health (SEARCH) Program
   (Grant # 2 H38 CS 00007-04).

   Health Professions Eligible:
     * Physician Assistant students
     * Nurse Practitioner students
     * Social Work students
     * Medical students and Residents

   Selection of Applicants:
   The following applicants will receive priority:
     * NHSC Scholars (top priority)
     * Students/Residents enrolled
       in an Alaskan or affiliated training program
     * Alaska residents
     * Students who send in applications by the following dates:
       November 1 for spring rotations (March - May)
       February 1 for summer rotations (June - August)
       May 1 for fall rotations (September - November)
       August 1 for winter rotations (December - February)

     * Other students will be accepted as resources allow.



                       logo, Alaskan Expsoure Program








   Location of Sites:
     * Underserved communities in a federally designated Health
       Professional Shortage Area or a Medically Underserved Area.
     * Communities are located on the road system or accessible only by
       air or water.

   Application Process:
     * Applications available to students through their Alaskan or
       affiliated training program
     * Other students may submit an application on-line or download a form
       in .pdf,

   Reimbursement:
     * A maximum amount is
       provided for airfare and meals.
     * Housing is either provided
       by the community or a
       modest allowance

   Why participate in the Alaskan Exposure Program?

   Students who participate in the Alaskan Exposure Program experience
   challenges, rewards, and cultural diversity that practicing in
   underserved communities can offer. Ideally, the Alaskan Exposure
   experience will encourage students to practice primary care in Alaska's
   underserved communities when they complete their individual training
   program.

   For questions, contact:

